CVM: Constrained variational optimization model with factorial designs

haiyan yu

7/16/2020

This document presents the stream of data processing, and the dignosis of the model. The four parts of diagnosis consist of discrepancy for blance check, trajectories of sampling, KLD for sampling compressiveness, parameter of the estimation (informativeness) and the value of both the compressiveness and the informativeness. causal variational model 1, dataxx[Treat.df == 1,“y”]): total samples, not only the treatment group data, cwdf_ebal;

2, cwdf_ebal[Treat.df == 1,“y”]): only the treatment group data, cwdf_ebal; cwdf_ebalT <- cwdf_ebal[treatment == 1,]

3, weights for the control, not selected

##Variance The weighted variance is the \(\Sigma (A_j, B_l)\) is the individial responses of each cells. That is estimated variance
\[{\hat \Sigma _i}({\hat V_l}) =\sum\nolimits_{i = 1}^{{N_{il}}} {\left( {\phi _i^2{{\hat \Sigma }_{il}}} \right)}.\] For $ Avg(({{V_l}}))$, it is the variance of the model. In the model, all of them assumed to be homoscedasticity.
\[ \hat V=\bar V+ \epsilon= \mu_0+ \beta_l+\tau_j+\epsilon, \epsilon \sim (0, \Sigma({{\hat V_l}})) \] The bias is the confounding error, \(e_l= \hat V_l-\bar V\), And the squared bias is
\[{\mathop{ \Sigma}} ({{\hat V_l(A, \phi)}}) = \frac{1}{{b-1}} \sum\limits_{i= 1}^b { {\left( {{{\hat V_l(A, \phi)}} - {{\hat V(A, \phi) }}} \right)^2} }.\] MSE: \[\Sigma =Avg(\hat \Sigma({{\hat V_l}})) + \left( {\frac{1}{{b }}} + 1\right) {\mathop{ \Sigma}} ({{\hat V_l}}), \]
